    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Sleep Gummies for Adults</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best dose of melatonin for adults?</summary><p>Research suggests 0.5-3mg is optimal for most adults. Higher doses do not proportionally improve sleep quality and may cause morning grogginess. Start with 1-3mg and increase only if needed.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are sleep gummies safe for long-term use?</summary><p>Short to medium-term use (up to 3 months) is considered safe. Long-term data is limited. Non-melatonin ingredients like L-theanine and magnesium have better long-term safety profiles. Consult a sleep specialist for chronic use.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can you become dependent on sleep gummies?</summary><p>Melatonin does not cause physical dependence. No withdrawal symptoms occur on discontinuation. Psychological dependence can develop with any sleep aid — use as part of a broader sleep hygiene strategy.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What ingredients besides melatonin help with sleep?</summary><p>L-theanine (200mg), magnesium glycinate (200-400mg), GABA (100-200mg), chamomile, passionflower, ashwagandha (300mg KSM-66), and CBD (25-50mg) all have evidence for sleep support.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>When should I take sleep gummies?</summary><p>30-60 minutes before target bedtime. Melatonin signals circadian timing, not sedation. Take at the same time nightly to reinforce your circadian rhythm.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do sleep gummies cause morning grogginess?</summary><p>Grogginess is typically caused by melatonin doses that are too high (above 5mg). Lower doses (0.5-3mg) or non-melatonin formulas (L-theanine, magnesium) reduce this risk.</p></details>

